  <!-- 1 ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="pose" data-status="done">
    <div class="sec-head"><span class="n">1</span><h2>The question, as posed</h2><span class="st">done</span></div>
    <p class="hint">State it in the asker's own words. Then name the <em>itch</em> — what makes this feel like a real, hanging question rather than a settled fact. The itch is the thing we're dissolving; the confusion lives in the map, not the territory.</p>
    <!-- FILL: pose -->
    <p>The posed question is: <strong>Is alcoholism a disease?</strong></p>
    <p>The itch is not mainly uncertainty about bottles, livers, cravings, promises, or ruined mornings. The itch comes from a yes/no label that seems to decide several high-stakes matters at once: whether the drinker deserves contempt or help, whether treatment or punishment makes sense, whether self-control still counts, whether family members may set hard boundaries, and whether insurers, courts, employers, or friends should respond as they would to a bodily ailment.</p>
    <p>Two internal handles collide. One handle says: drinking is an action performed by a person; actions invite responsibility, incentives, trust, blame, apology, and repair. The other says: repeated drinking can keep happening after sincere vows, losses, shame, withdrawal, craving, and visible harm; that looks less like ordinary preference and more like a process that has partly escaped simple command. The word <em>disease</em> is asked to settle that collision by category membership. The territory contains patterns, mechanisms, choices, harms, and interventions. The map-confusion is asking one word to distribute all the moral and practical consequences.</p>
    <!-- /FILL: pose -->
  </section>

  <!-- 2 ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="taboo" data-status="done">
    <div class="sec-head"><span class="n">2</span><h2>Taboo the words</h2><span class="st">done</span></div>
    <p class="hint">Ban the loaded word (<em>free will</em>, <em>disease</em>, <em>fair</em>, <em>conscious</em>, <em>really</em>) and re-ask using only what you actually mean. Where the substitution flows, the word was cheap. Where you <em>cannot</em> substitute without smuggling the word back — that spot is the confusion, now located.</p>
    <!-- FILL: taboo -->
    <table><thead><tr><th>Banned word</th><th>What it was standing in for</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">alcoholism</span></span></td><td>A recurring pattern in which a person drinks in ways that bring predictable harm, violate later or prior intentions, and disrupt health, relationships, work, safety, or self-respect. If this pattern is absent, the original question has no target.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">disease</span>, <span class="from">illness</span>, <span class="from">disorder</span>, <span class="from">pathology</span>, <span class="from">medical condition</span></span></td><td>A packed cluster: bodily or learned mechanisms, impaired control, need for treatment, eligibility for care, reduced contempt, possible accommodation, and a different style of accountability.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">real</span>, <span class="from">really</span>, <span class="from">true</span>, <span class="from">actually</span></span></td><td>A request for a privileged category after the observable facts are already fixed. Replace it with: what would we expect to observe, and what response would change?</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">just</span>, <span class="from">merely</span>, <span class="from">only</span></span></td><td>An attempt to collapse a multi-cause pattern into one small description, usually either "bad choice" or "body problem," while discarding the rest.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">choice</span>, <span class="from">voluntary</span></span></td><td>Actions that can respond to reasons, incentives, planning, threat, promise, habit, environment, and available help. This comes in degrees and contexts, not one switch.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="taboo-pair"><span class="from">responsible</span>, <span class="from">blameworthy</span>, <span class="from">moral failing</span></span></td><td>Questions about which responses help: trust or distrust, help or refusal, treatment or punishment, compassion or anger, repair demands or exclusion.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <p>Taboo rewrite: Does the person show a recurring harmful drinking pattern; what mechanisms keep it going; how much does it respond to ordinary reasons and changed circumstances; which interventions reduce harm; and which forms of accountability produce better outcomes?</p>
    <p>The irreplaceable word has been located. If the intended question means "should this pattern receive the social status attached to the medical label?", the taboo rewrite stalls because the label itself is the prize being contested. That is not an extra fact hiding inside the drinker; it is a fight over how to sort compassion, payment, coercion, blame, and help.</p>
    <!-- /FILL: taboo -->
  </section>

  <!-- 3 ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="trace" data-status="done">
    <div class="sec-head"><span class="n">3</span><h2>Stack trace &amp; sub-questions</h2><span class="st">done</span></div>
    <p class="hint">Write the trace of the mental algorithm that <em>generates the feeling of a question</em> — not an answer to it. Then unbundle: a disguised question is usually several separate questions wearing one word. Diagram the decomposition.</p>
    <!-- FILL: trace -->
    <p>Stack trace of the felt question:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>The mind notices a pattern: a person drinks again after losses, promises, warnings, shame, or danger.</li>
      <li>One classifier fires: drinking is an intentional act. Intentional acts invite criticism, incentives, promises, consequences, apology, and repair.</li>
      <li>Another classifier fires: the repetition looks self-defeating and sticky. Craving, habit, withdrawal, social cues, distress, and bodily adaptation make "simply stop" predict poorly.</li>
      <li>The classifiers import social packages. The action-package says blame and discipline. The ailment-package says treatment, patience, care, and less contempt.</li>
      <li>The word <em>alcoholism</em> hides assumptions that need their own tests: that the pattern is recurring, harmful, hard to interrupt, and not merely a single disliked choice.</li>
      <li>The word <em>disease</em> is then asked to choose a package. If yes, help; if no, blame. Because the package decides family behavior, law, medicine, self-image, and shame, the label feels urgent.</li>
      <li>The mind searches for a hidden essence that will authorize one package. The dissolution is to stop searching for that essence and separate the facts from the decision rules.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Unbundled sub-questions:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Target pattern:</strong> Does the person repeatedly drink in ways that predictably produce harm or violate their own intentions?</li>
      <li><strong>Control dynamics:</strong> Are urges, withdrawal, habit, cues, or distress strong enough that ordinary resolution often fails?</li>
      <li><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Are bodily or learned processes sustaining the pattern?</li>
      <li><strong>Intervention:</strong> Do treatment, support, environmental changes, or medication-like help reduce harm better than shame or exhortation alone?</li>
      <li><strong>Agency:</strong> Does the person still respond to reasons, incentives, planning, commitments, or consequences in some contexts?</li>
      <li><strong>Extra essence:</strong> After all those answers are known, is there a further fact about belonging to the special category?</li>
      <li><strong>Policy/value:</strong> Which stance toward the person produces better outcomes: compassion, treatment, boundaries, sanctions, repair demands, or some mix?</li>
    </ul>
