  <section id="anticipate" data-status="done">
    <div class="sec-head"><span class="n">4</span><h2>Reduce to anticipated experience</h2><span class="st">done</span></div>
    <p class="hint">Turn each sub-question into what you'd actually <em>expect to observe</em> if it went one way versus the other. A sub-question whose two answers predict the same experience is <em>empty</em> — mark it dissolved-on-contact. The rest are real and may need evidence.</p>
    <!-- FILL: anticipate -->
    <table><thead><tr><th>Sub-question</th><th>If yes, I'd anticipate…</th><th>If no, I'd anticipate…</th><th>Verdict</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Target pattern: recurring harmful drinking?</td><td>Repeated episodes, predictable losses or risks, failed cutbacks, concealment, repair attempts, and a history that lets others forecast harm.</td><td>Occasional or disliked drinking without a stable harmful pattern; no reliable forecast of repeated damage from the drinking itself.</td><td>empirical</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Control dynamics: ordinary resolution often fails?</td><td>Sincere intentions break under cues, stress, withdrawal, availability, habit, or craving; changed environments and supports alter outcomes.</td><td>Stated intentions track behavior about as well as in ordinary preference changes; incentives and plans work without special support.</td><td>empirical</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mechanism: bodily or learned processes sustain it?</td><td>Tolerance, withdrawal-like discomfort, cue-triggered wanting, relief cycles, or practiced routines that persist across occasions.</td><td>No such recurring mechanisms; the pattern is explained by current preferences, local incentives, or isolated circumstances.</td><td>empirical</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intervention: help beats shame alone?</td><td>Structured support, treatment, changed surroundings, medication-like tools, or planned boundaries reduce episodes and harm better than scolding.</td><td>Scolding, threat, or ordinary exhortation works as well as or better than supportive or medical-style interventions.</td><td>empirical</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Agency: reasons and consequences still matter?</td><td>Behavior varies with access, monitoring, commitments, costs, relationships, plans, and incentives; accountability can shape future behavior.</td><td>Behavior is invariant under reasons, incentives, plans, costs, and social context; ordinary accountability has no predictive effect.</td><td>empirical</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Extra essence after facts are known?</td><td>No new observation follows. The same person, episodes, mechanisms, and intervention results remain under a prestigious label.</td><td>No new observation follows. The same person, episodes, mechanisms, and intervention results remain under a non-prestigious label.</td><td>empty</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Policy/value: use compassion, help, boundaries, and repair rather than contempt?</td><td>If this stance is chosen and its empirical assumptions hold, I would expect earlier disclosure, less pointless humiliation, more treatment uptake, clearer boundaries, and more targeted repair.</td><td>If a contempt-first stance is chosen, I would expect deterrence only where shame and threat work; otherwise hiding, escalation, brittle trust, and less useful help.</td><td>value</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
