+    <div class="sec-head"><span class="n">1</span><h2>The question, as posed</h2><span class="st">done</span></div>
     <p class="hint">State it in the asker's own words. Then name the <em>itch</em> — what makes this feel like a real, hanging question rather than a settled fact. The itch is the thing we're dissolving; the confusion lives in the map, not the territory.</p>
     <!-- FILL: pose -->
-    <p></p>
+    <p>The posed question is: <strong>Is alcoholism a disease?</strong></p>
+    <p>The itch is not mainly uncertainty about bottles, livers, cravings, promises, or ruined mornings. The itch comes from a yes/no label that seems to decide several high-stakes matters at once: whether the drinker deserves contempt or help, whether treatment or punishment makes sense, whether self-control still counts, whether family members may set hard boundaries, and whether insurers, courts, employers, or friends should respond as they would to a bodily ailment.</p>
+    <p>Two internal handles collide. One handle says: drinking is an action performed by a person; actions invite responsibility, incentives, trust, blame, apology, and repair. The other says: repeated drinking can keep happening after sincere vows, losses, shame, withdrawal, craving, and visible harm; that looks less like ordinary preference and more like a process that has partly escaped simple command. The word <em>disease</em> is asked to settle that collision by category membership. The territory contains patterns, mechanisms, choices, harms, and interventions. The map-confusion is asking one word to distribute all the moral and practical consequences.</p>
     <!-- /FILL: pose -->
   </section>
 
