     <p class="hint">State the dissolution: with the word tabooed and the sub-questions separated, the original question is answered, empty, or replaced by sharper ones. Then run the gate — <em>is there any lingering feeling of a hanging question?</em> If yes, it is not dissolved; note where the pull remains and keep going.</p>
     <!-- FILL: resolution -->
-    <p class="verdict"></p>
-    <p><span class="label">Lingering-confusion check</span><br></p>
+    <p class="verdict">With the loaded label removed, the original question becomes a bundle of sharper questions about recurring harmful drinking, impaired control, sustaining mechanisms, intervention results, remaining agency, and response policy. The remaining bare question, "but does it belong to the special category?", is empty once those observations are fixed.</p>
+    <p>For the surviving decision question, settle by consequences. A useful stance treats the pattern as harmful and partly self-propelling while preserving practical accountability: reduce triggers, offer effective help, keep boundaries, require repair where repair helps, and use blame only where blame improves prediction, prevention, or restitution. "What is deserved in the hidden essence sense?" adds no testable handle; "what response helps?" does the work.</p>
+    <p><span class="label">Lingering-confusion check</span><br>Rereading "Is alcoholism a disease?", I do not feel a remaining need for a yes/no label as an extra fact. The old pull is recognizable: people use the label as a passkey for compassion, care, payment, coercion, or exemption from contempt. Once those are named separately, the hanging feeling drains away. What remains is not the original category mystery but empirical uncertainty about cases and a value choice about policy.</p>
     <p><span class="label">Open threads</span></p>
-    <ul></ul>
+    <ul>
+      <li>Specific cases still need evidence: severity, recurrence, harms, control dynamics, and response to changed circumstances.</li>
+      <li>Interventions should be judged by outcomes for the person and affected others, not by loyalty to a label.</li>
+      <li>Policy still contains tradeoffs among compassion, safety, autonomy, trust, cost, and repair; those are decisions to make openly.</li>
+    </ul>
     <!-- /FILL: resolution -->
   </section>
 
