+    <p>Stack trace of the felt question:</p>
+    <ol>
+      <li>The mind notices a pattern: a person drinks again after losses, promises, warnings, shame, or danger.</li>
+      <li>One classifier fires: drinking is an intentional act. Intentional acts invite criticism, incentives, promises, consequences, apology, and repair.</li>
+      <li>Another classifier fires: the repetition looks self-defeating and sticky. Craving, habit, withdrawal, social cues, distress, and bodily adaptation make "simply stop" predict poorly.</li>
+      <li>The classifiers import social packages. The action-package says blame and discipline. The ailment-package says treatment, patience, care, and less contempt.</li>
+      <li>The word <em>alcoholism</em> hides assumptions that need their own tests: that the pattern is recurring, harmful, hard to interrupt, and not merely a single disliked choice.</li>
+      <li>The word <em>disease</em> is then asked to choose a package. If yes, help; if no, blame. Because the package decides family behavior, law, medicine, self-image, and shame, the label feels urgent.</li>
+      <li>The mind searches for a hidden essence that will authorize one package. The dissolution is to stop searching for that essence and separate the facts from the decision rules.</li>
+    </ol>
+    <p>Unbundled sub-questions:</p>
+    <ul>
+      <li><strong>Target pattern:</strong> Does the person repeatedly drink in ways that predictably produce harm or violate their own intentions?</li>
+      <li><strong>Control dynamics:</strong> Are urges, withdrawal, habit, cues, or distress strong enough that ordinary resolution often fails?</li>
+      <li><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Are bodily or learned processes sustaining the pattern?</li>
+      <li><strong>Intervention:</strong> Do treatment, support, environmental changes, or medication-like help reduce harm better than shame or exhortation alone?</li>
+      <li><strong>Agency:</strong> Does the person still respond to reasons, incentives, planning, commitments, or consequences in some contexts?</li>
+      <li><strong>Extra essence:</strong> After all those answers are known, is there a further fact about belonging to the special category?</li>
+      <li><strong>Policy/value:</strong> Which stance toward the person produces better outcomes: compassion, treatment, boundaries, sanctions, repair demands, or some mix?</li>
+    </ul>
